data: The Rubber Man disappears and Tate appears. He and Violet go on their date to the beach and Tate tells her high school was terrible for him. Five mangled, bloody teens appear and harass Tate, prompting the couple to leave. Vivien tells Ben that Hayden is in the house. Ben finds her in the basement, but Larry knocks him out with the shovel and ties him up. Nora frees him, urging him to save his child. Hayden appears to Vivien and both are shocked to learn that the other is pregnant with Ben’s child. Hayden attacks her, but is stopped by Ben, who is forced to admit that he impregnated Hayden months after Vivien discovered the affair. The teens find Tate and Violet, but Tate protects Violet by making them chase him. Constance takes Violet to her house, revealing that Addie is dead and Tate is her son. The teens are revealed to be ghosts from various cliques at Westview High who were killed when Tate committed a school shooting in 1994. The ghosts angrily demand to know why he killed them and that he admit what he did, but Tate cannot remember anything about them. With Halloween night ending, the teens depart. The other ghosts including Moira, Chad, Patrick, and Nora warily return to the house. Ben packs and sadly leaves the house.

In 1994, Larry, in love with Constance, mercy-kills her deformed son, Beau, who lives chained in the attic, at Constance’s request upon learning that Beau would be taken away from her due to her neglectful parenting. In the present, Violet takes solace in Tate, who says he is aware of the ghosts and that they will not harm her if she tells them to leave her alone. He shows her old photographs he found of the house and the Montgomerys. Vivien learns she is pregnant with twins. Resolved to be upfront with prospective buyers about the house’s past, she learns of the Montgomerys and that Charles revived their son into a monster, causing Nora to go insane and kill him and herself. Ben finds Larry’s home and confronts him, learning that Larry wants the house so he can be with Constance. Violet shares the photos of the Montgomerys with Vivien, who is shocked to find that she recognizes Nora as one of the interested buyers in Episode 3.

Ben goes to pick Vivien up at the sanitarium, intent on taking Violet with him. Violet however, being a ghost, is trapped on the property. He takes Vivien home to pick up Violet as Vivien insists on going to her sister's Florida home. While waiting in the car, Vivien begins to have labor pains. Violet tries to explain to her father that she is dead. Constance brings Vivien into the house and goes to get "help" to assist in the delivery—the ghosts of Dr. Charles Montgomery and the 1968 nurses show up for the task. During the labor, Violet is told by Chad that Tate was the one who sired one of the twins. Vivien has great difficulty in birthing both babies, losing one to stillbirth while the other causes her to bleed internally. Violet appears to comfort her mother asks her to "come be with her." Vivien dies and Violet confronts Tate, telling him she loves him but can never forgive him. She screams for him to go away and he does. Vivien appears and comforts her daughter in the afterlife.

Vivien has great difficulty in birthing both babies, losing one to stillbirth while the other causes her to bleed internally. Violet appears to comfort her mother asks her to "come be with her." Vivien dies and Violet confronts Tate, telling him she loves him but can never forgive him. She screams for him to go away and he does. Vivien appears and comforts her daughter in the afterlife.

Ben, feeling alone, plans to commit suicide, but Violet's and Vivien's ghosts encourage him to take the living twin and get out of the house. During his attempt, he is killed by Hayden and the home-invader ghosts, hanged from the chandelier; Constance takes the living twin. Moira and other "innocent" ghosts help the Harmon ghosts prevent the deaths of further tenants by scaring away the first family that wants to move in, the Ramoses. Tate, feeling alienated, tries to kill the Ramos son, so Violet won't be alone. She prevents this by distracting Tate. Nora, who wants a child since hers was murdered and turned evil, relinquishes motherhood of the dead Harmon twin to Vivien, who asks Moira to be a godmother. The Harmons and Moira decorate the house for Christmas, while Tate tells Hayden he will wait "forever" for Violet. Three years later, Constance comes home and sees a trail of blood on the floor, leading to the bedroom of the living Harmon twin, now about 3-years-old and looking much like Tate. He has murdered his nanny and is sitting in a rocking chair, smiling up at Constance.

data: "Annette and Lucien" "Anetto Ya Rushian" (アネットやルシアン)

The story begins in the Swiss village of Rossinière c. the final year of the 19th century where our heroine Annette Burnier is getting bootstrapped to begin her day by the reminder of a promise to catalyze the assumption of responsibility for the cows; a session of maternal criticism on the part of her pregnant mother Francine later, Annette rushes off to find her father Pierre milking the cows with the volition that she feed the cows. The conversation that Annette prosecutes with a neighbor becomes the vehicle by which Annette's best friend Lucien Morel is introduced as having much more dire misfortune since his family is without his dead father serving as the primary breadwinner and the man of the house -- the latter Lucien cannot easily fulfill as evidenced by the session of turbulent family government with his mother Elizabeth; while prosecuting the school commute, an ambush by the class bully Jean and the aftermath thereof becomes the backdrop against which Annette and Lucien's relationship is defined. Driven by his "kill-the-king" emphasis on the circumstantial epilogue, Lucien attempts an ill-planned prank with an estivating lizard to get even with Jean only to ultimately find himself facing Sensei Nicholas along with being embroiled in a vivacious adversarial divergent concourse with Annette after school; while Annette only has to worry about what to name her neonatal sibling, Lucien and his older sister Marie find themselves facing the urgent necessity of forestalling imminent homelessness to the tune of fifty francs.

"The Day of the Sled Riding Contest"

The entire community of Rossinière mourning with Burnier-ke during the burial of the carcass that was once Francine Burnier is an endearing sight that ignores the reality of Annette literally trapped in her mother's final moments before the low-on-fuel outcry her neonate little brother Daniel jolts her back into reality along with Pierre's admonition for Annette to stop crying; while the intentions behind their visit are good, Marie and Lucien's encouragement complete with a homemade dinner prompts Annette to leap to the other extreme of taking her mother's final words to heart as she throws herself into maintaining Daniel along with operating things at the proverbial ranch. It soon becomes apparent to Pierre that he and Annette are in over their heads; further inflaming matters, Annette is in denial about how best to solve the matter of raising Daniel and continuing her education when she suggests bringing Daniel to school with her -- that school day being quite an adventure because of and in spite of her very supportive classmates!!! Seeing the impact of Annette foregoing her childhood to maintain Daniel along with facing a week's worth of school assignments each time she goes to visit Sensei Nicholas, Pierre's computation ultimately gives way to realizing that Annette should not have the choice about the homeostasis of maintaining Daniel and prosecuting her schoolwork along with the housework necessary to operate Burnier-ke; however, it is quite another matter for Pierre to come above-ground with his decision to explain his aunt Claude Marta the necessity for her assistance at Burnier-ke and to demonstrate the family government to take away the choice about whether Annette cooperates.

The veracity of the adjective typical having never been a word to describe an afternoon at Burnier-ke jumps exponentially when Pierre's aunt Claude Marta arrives in Rossinière from Montreux after having undergone a lengthy and bumpy carriage ride; while Mr. Heide tries to arrange for someone to set course to Burnier-ke with Claude, Annette is busy isolating dandelion leaves as her neonate little brother Daniel continues to slumber. Upon seeing Lucien arrive, Annette takes the opportunity to head inside but soon finds that Lucien taking a catnap while Daniel playfully tugs at Pepper's ears much to the canine's discomfort is the least of her worries when she finds herself face-to-face with Claude who is not slow in laying down some ground rules nor in appraising the house to find that her help is more sorely needed than Pierre wrote in his letter to her; the next morning, Annette finds several signs that Claude has really made herself at home as evidenced by faultlessly detecting that Daniel is announcing the release of his exhaust rather than being low on fuel. Much to her astonishment, Annette finds that Claude hits the ground running with a curriculum to ultimately set Burnier-ke on course for a new homeostasis that enables Annette's return to school among other things; as if to celebrate Annette's return to doing the normal things that a child does, the whole adventure of Annette and Lucien being led through catalyzing the accouchement of a calf inspires the advent of a whole new perspective of Claude Marta.

It is summertime in Rossinière which Pierre reads as his signal to lead his bovine herd to the meadows nestled within the Alps mountain range as evidenced by Annette happily ushering the cattle out of the barn; upon Lucien arriving with his mother, Pierre isolates two of the cows prior to setting course for his mountain cabin with Annette and Lucien accompanying him. In spite of his good intentions, Pierre inadvertently ignites Annette's jealous ire with his promise to instruct Lucien in using a scythe and his obliviousness to Annette's umbrage at the covert sexism; while Pierre divides his energies toward prosecuting the journey to the cabin and wondering if he has possibly put his foot in his mouth, Claude and Mrs. Morel exchange prologues over a spot of tea as the two women get better acquainted with each other. The mountain cabin where Pierre will house himself with Annette and Lucien requires a lot of housekeeping before it becomes habitable; as has been previously demonstrated, Annette and Lucien's zealous refurbishment efforts stir up a huge dust cloud that stifles respiration and ends up reigniting the earlier adversarial divergent concourse. Pierre taking the time to guide Lucien through properly using the scythe while also charging the frustrated Annette vigilance over the cattle before leaving makes it clear that Annette has not learned that she cannot always have things her way -- particularly because Lucien has gleaned enough data to ascertain and ultimately stalemate her attempt to sweet-talk him into letting her use the scythe; now having been literally demonstrated an incidence of very weighty beef courtesy of the calf Rosette and a particularly steep declivity that requires a canine intercession from Pepper, Annette and Lucien realize the immense wisdom in burying the hatchet.

The effects of Annette's impromptu excursion are not slow in manifesting at Burnier-ke as evidenced by Claude searching for Daniel only to find Pepper bound fast to the house with Annette's schoolbag next to him; as the scope of her grand-niece's curriculum starts to unfold before Claude, Annette is starting to panic as she sees the conductor talking with Daniel who is playing the role of a lost boy traveling with his family government as the train begins to accelerate before she has the procedure for accessing the cabin demonstrated for her. As can be predicted from a child within its first half-decade, Daniel's cerebral software does not have the refinement to understand that stowing away on a train is not an insignificant taboo as evidenced by his replies which would have given away Annette's presence if taken seriously; while Annette divides her energies between prosecuting various tactics to evade detection and computing how to reverse course back to Rossinière with Daniel, Pierre and the Rossinière station-master are starting to realize the seriousness of the situation as each of the in-line stations report not sighting the Burnier siblings. What Annette does not realize is that Pierre has ultimately made an educated guess that she and Daniel are headed to the Montreux terminus where she plans to reverse course back home the same way; even with prosecuting an emphatic display of being Daniel's cousin and Marie serving a chaperone for the return trip, Annette cannot escape the turbulent family government with which Pierre and Claude congratulate her for her adventurous stewardship which involves a right hullabaloo upon the Montreux station-master detecting them.

As has been previously demonstrated, Pierre ultimately ends up interjecting a hitch in the get-a-long when he explains Annette that Mr. Fernand has taken Lucien under his wing for the summer while an ill-considered comment on Annette's part hints at reconciliation with Lucien being a not-too-distant possibility; even if Annette has not made as much progress toward embracing the idea of proximity to Lucien, Daniel does start off the whole visit to Mr. Fernand by delightedly demonstrating Lucien his prowess in effecting altitude changes on stairs and from wheeled conveyances.

Even before Annette's arrival to prompt him, it takes a while for Daniel to bootstrap himself to the reality that he has arrived at the Burnier-ke mountain cabin and that he needs to catalyze Pierre milking the cows; while Daniel is delighted at Annette's tutelage bearing fruit, what is not so straightforward is how to make Annette's grudge with Lucien cost-prohibitive. Galvanized by Pierre's exhortation that she reconsider her frigidity regarding Lucien before departing with Daniel, Annette starts to recall the first visit to the Burnier-ke mountain cabin with Lucien who had been a net positive in spite of her having been rather ill-tempered without cause; a session of tussling around with Daniel to stop him from scattering around a pile of grass later, Annette's classmate Marianne arrives with the news of a summer picnic near Jean's cabin at which Daniel insists upon attending along with unwisely inquiring about Lucien's lack of an RSVP. The subsequent euphoric diurnal engagement proves that Annette and Lucien ultimately do not hate each other to the point where the two spending time together is impossible; still, there does need to be an external catalyst -- one the potency of Daniel's ill-timed comment -- for Annette's computations to crest the mountain about the benefits of joyously co-existing with Lucien who has moved on with his life.

What appears to be a blandly routine morning will soon become quite colorful when Sensei Nicholas arrives exhausted from his hike to the mountains; setting that aside, Daniel is anguished to find that the bill for overstaying his week-long welcome has come due -- a fact that Annette and Pierre have every intention of enforcing no matter how much he protests. Annette's workday upon seeing off Daniel after Pierre mounts him and departs becomes the backdrop for Sensei Nicholas to arrive with several of her classmates in convoy; an adversarial divergent concourse about the balance between honesty and tact later, Sensei Nicholas signals the necessity for a place to offload his backpack so that he can more easily ascend the mountain in a bid to collect the flora that grows there. Disliking how she has had the choice of whether to watch the cabin taken away from her, Annette looks over at the sleeping Pepper as she recalls Pierre's remarks about how the canine is more than enough to watch both cabin and bovine; galvanized at successfully utilizing this data to her advantage and the opportunity to converse with Lucien without losing face, Annette resumes her intercept course toward the western mountain pastures oblivious to the dark clouds anticipating a rainstorm. The influx of fog serves to ultimately demonstrate that it is indeed possible to get Sensei Nicholas in over his head; while it is not as bad as Daniel's was, Sensei Nicholas's structural deceleration damage does render him non-ambulatory to where he has the choice of whether to stopover on Burnier-ke taken away from him.

The now-destroyed equine carving evokes equally emphatic and starkly contrasting reactions within both Annette and Lucien -- the former returning home empty-handed while the latter races off in a blind panic upon recalling Annette declaring Daniel's injury irreversible as Mrs. Morel tries to shift the conversation to constructive action; while Annette frantically tries to deflect Claude's inquiries, Lucien decides to march right over to Burnier-ke to demand answers as why Annette destroyed his handiwork before it becomes clear that this would not do him any good since the original problem has not been solved. The crafts exhibition the next day becomes quite a colorful event when Daniel's childish behavior draws unwanted attention to Annette's handiwork not unlike a bull in a china shop; even if one ignores the kindergartener getting lost in a bid to catch Klaus, Daniel successfully polluting the judge's computations about who should win the contest on Annette's behalf re-ignites Lucien's earlier suspicion. Lacking the courage to confront Annette about unjustly winning that contest, Lucien ultimately decides that suicide is the only real solution; while Mr. Peguin comes in quite handy for a desperately needed rescue bootstrapping to shock him out of his hysteria prior to the home commute, Annette has the epiphany that victory can at times be worse than defeat as she breaks down crying when she recalls Lucien's crestfallen face.

As if to congratulate Annette having confessed her crime and Lucien having already seen past it, the snowstorm's apace resumption prompts Claude to anxiously ponder to herself why her grandniece would unnecessarily risk deadly hypothermia when Pierre stops in to regroup; meanwhile, Lucien is finding that Annette is more badly damaged than he realizes in spite of his hard-won proximity to Burnier-ke. A jovial evening is had as Pierre and Claude busy themselves with repairing Annette along with visiting hospitable gratitude unto Lucien; still, everything is not all hunky-dory as evidenced by Annette deciding for a diurnal engagement with Sensei Nicholas to redress her dishonest victory in the crafts competition. Sensei Nicholas is astonished that the class clown Lucien Morel that he has ordered to the rear of the classroom with a bucket of water over his head has such carpentry prowess but ultimately agrees to do what Annette wants; still, with that out of the way, the question remains of how to repair Daniel so that reliance on crutches is not life-long ...

The lack of definitive data as to Lucien's whereabouts even with Pierre having searched all night is disconcerting for Annette who wakes up from a nightmare; still, she need not have worried since Lucien has safely arrived in Montreux where he comes upon Dr. Givet about to depart for the train station. Galvanized at the sight of Lucien's physiological contention, Dr. Givet sequesters Lucien in a room where he begins to compose some questions for the tweenager starting with the large sum of money in his possession; much to Lucien's relief, Dr. Givet has no qualms about agreeing to repair Daniel upon hearing of the tweenager's adventure through the mountain pass but still has a few unanswered questions -- a few of which he tries to get Lucien to answer during the train ride to Rossinière. Much to the delight of Burnier-ke, Dr. Givet is of expertise enough to ultimately determine that Daniel's right leg has clumsily healed and knows of a way to reverse the anomaly; while the decision to have Annette along for the trip to Lausanne successfully appeases the unhappy Daniel, Dr. Givet signals an interest in Mr. Peguin's cabin as a destination not realizing that his curiosity will make things quite turbulent for Lucien ...

Seeing Lucien race toward his cabin with news of having successfully sought out Dr. Givet's medical intercession definitely makes Mr. Peguin's day; still, Annette's arrival with Dr. Givet lands Lucien in quite a pickle that sets the stage for Lucien and Annette to learn quite a history lesson about the elderly carpenter. Lucien already knew that Mr. Peguin was a fallen career/family man that got caught up in the criminal justice system but not that a sentimental father-son reunion would be Dr. Givet's service fee for repairing Daniel; while Dr. Givet and Mr. Peguin are clearing the air, there is still the matter of the two months needed to fully rehabilitate Daniel. The Burnier-ke dinner table concourse is quite vivaciously defined in terms of the contrast between Lausanne and Rossinière along with a reminder of how Annette and Daniel are to behave at Givet-ke -- an incidence of which when Daniel unwisely asks about Klaus coming along for the ride; meanwhile, over at Morel-ke, Lucien is anguished to learn that Marie plans to return to Montreux which is where Dr. Givet will lead the Burnier siblings through interchanging for the train to Lausanne. Not much of the train journey has to pass before Daniel is ultimately as adamant about Klaus's proximity as he is about having Annette nearby; fortunately, Dr. Givet already knows that Klaus is very important to Daniel and takes the whole matter in stride as the train approaches Montreux.

As would be expected of a child within its first half-decade, Daniel is not shy about indicating novel scenery features nor is he slow in recounting his previous adventure on the train much to Annette's chagrin; while en route to Montreux, Marie reminds Annette the importance of complying Dr. Givet's counsel about learning the lay of the land in Lausanne along with constant correspondence -- the latter being exactly what Claude and Pierre could use as they come to grips with how quiet Burnier-ke has become. Lucien fuming at Mr. Peguin teasing him about his infatuation with Annette gives way to the fact that the Burnier siblings have quite a syllabus ahead of them starting with the lead butler Willelm and the quantum leap of urban opulence that is Lausanne. The majesty of the Givet-ke mansion is quite tame compared to Dr. Givet's son Marc taking quite well to Klaus much to Daniel's delight while Annette is astonished at how much of a flawless emulation Dr. Givet's spouse Helena is of her late mother Francine!!! As if having sensed Lucien's visit to Burnier-ke, Annette's homesickness ultimately reaches its peak as she composes a letter explaining her safe arrival with Daniel along with her experiences with Givet-ke; in a bid to help Annette cope, Helena bails the anguished tweenager her infant son Culé.

As has become the case as of late, Lucien finds that his school commute has gotten off course as he reads Annette's account of her adventures in Lausanne -- a chapter of which involves Daniel illegally enjoying Klaus's proximity which gets him in hot water with Mrs. Pauel -- along with a desire to see Franz again; as Lucien's proposal of correspondence with Annette gathers steam with the other kids, Dr. Givet returns an ETA of five days before Daniel is to have his surgery which will have some painful rehabilitative down-time in tow while Helena entreats peaceful co-existence of Elisabeth on Annette's behalf. Even with Klaus's presence, the trepidation over the next ten dozen hours ultimately reaches its peak at the arrival of zero hour; even with several assurances and supportive gestures from Givet-ke -- the most astonishing of which from the frigid Elisabeth, there is still the anguishing reality that doctors are fallible human beings that cannot completely control the circumstances ...

The turbulence of Annette's scholastic difficulty with arithmetic subsides a great deal when Elisabeth intercedes an angry coachman on Annette's behalf during a rainy-day rendezvous -- a gesture indicative of Elisabeth finally on board with the idea of Annette as a friend; galvanized at the news of Daniel's successful operation, Franz's surprise visit is exactly what the doctor ordered for Annette to decompress -- a walk around the grounds and a sightseeing tour of Lausanne. Galvanized by the ETA of spring's arrival when she and Daniel can go home, Pierre pipes up with a desire to head to Lausanne in order to ultimately get the truth from the horse's mouth much to Lucien's delight; while Daniel's frustration of his agony drives him to have a nightmare and to refuse breakfast much to Annette's dismay, a morning nap awakens Daniel to a new reality -- the weighted traction no longer being necessary!!!

Upon arriving at Givet-ke, Lucien finds it rather awkward to be the man of the hour when his mountain pass adventure is unwisely availed as an ice breaker -- an epilogue anticipated by Lucien's earlier mistaken impression of Wilhelm; as if having heard Mrs. Morel recounting Marie's decision regarding her wedding date, Daniel exerts an effort to power through his trepidation as he complies Dr. Givet's request to bend his knee upon his cast being removed. The time in Lausanne ultimately draws to a close with there being no doubt that both Burnier-ke and Givet-ke have become quite cohesive; still, Claude is astonished at Daniel's decision of how to answer the question of whether the endo-skeletal repair job is a success -- a leap from the train complete with a running bear hug!!!

Daniel's successful birth, her mother Francine dying from said accouchement, finding herself in over her head maintaining both the house and Daniel along with her studies, meeting her grand-aunt Claude Marta, Daniel drawing her into an interurban adventure on a passenger train, the ermine Klaus causing all sorts of hullabaloo, Daniel's deceleration damage having been found to be of such an insidious scope that ignites a cold war with Lucien because of the clumsy medical appraisal/repair attempts, dunked with a frigid epiphany regarding her folly ... Annette has definitely undergone a lot of trauma and caused a lot of drama that interfered Daniel being successfully repaired -- the demonstration of which being when Daniel rushes to the pasture with lunch in tow; while there is mirth in Daniel's attempts to chase away the impatient Pepper, there are not a few loose ends to tie up -- Mr. Peguin's decision to head to Givet-ke in Lausanne, Marie bringing home her fiancé César Baroux, a silly divergent concourse over voyeurism, Marie getting married, and the question of what to do in the future. Not realizing its significance, Daniel pipes up to ultimately propose matrimony of Annette and Lucien -- a proposal that really hits close to home and livens up the concourse; the matriculation from primary school having run its bittersweet course, Lucien pipes up with the idea for everybody to meet at the bridge once a month before leading the charge to Morel-ke upon learning of the gifts that Marie and César have brought with them.

data: When Johnny's policeman friend is injured in a car crash, the paramedics can't reach the hospital because another squad is using the biophone. Roy and John finally restore their old fire engine to ride in the California Fire Fighters Parade. A man with heart problems insists on driving, and causes an accident for which the other driver blames herself. Dixie and Dr. Early treat a patient who has a seizure in the waiting room. The title refers to the code word for "wild animal loose, threatening". The show opens with Johnny and Roy on a pre-dawn call to a small grocery store for a man down, bleeding. Searching the back of the store, Johnny is confronted with a Bengal tiger! A big brush fire threatens a suburban canyon area with lots of domesticated animals and things get dicey all around for the fire department and the Animal Control guys. Rampart becomes a veterinary surgical center for a while.
